  ', 'Your codespace will open once ready.', 'There was a problem preparing your codespace, please try again.', 'An OrderedSet is a mutable data structure that is a hybrid of a list and a set.
It remembers the order of its entries, and every entry has an index number that
can be looked up.', ' is available on PyPI and packaged as a wheel. You can list it
as a dependency of your project, in whatever form that takes.', 'To install it into your current Python environment:', 'To install the code for development, after checking out the repository:', 'An OrderedSet is created and used like a set:', 'It is efficient to find the index of an entry in an OrderedSet, or find an
entry by its index. To help with this use case, the ', ' method returns
the index of the added item, whether it was already in the set or not.', 'OrderedSets implement the union (', '), intersection (', '), and difference (', ')
operators like sets do.', 'The ', ' and ', ' methods have been extended to accept any
iterable except a string, returning a list, to perform NumPy-like "fancy
indexing".', 'OrderedSet implements ', ' and ', ' so it can be pickled,
and implements the abstract base classes ', ' and
', '.', 'OrderedSet can be used as a generic collection type, similar to the collections
in the ', ' module like List, Dict, and Set. For example, you can annotate
a variable as having the type ', ' or ', '.', 'An OrderedSet can be used as a bi-directional mapping between a sparse
vocabulary and dense index numbers. As of version 3.1, it accepts NumPy arrays
of index numbers as well as lists.', 'This combination of features makes OrderedSet a simple implementation of many
of the things that ', ' is used for, and many of its operations are
faster than the equivalent pandas operations.', 'For further compatibility with pandas.Index, ', ' (the pandas method for
looking up a single index) and ', ' (the pandas method for fancy
indexing in reverse) are both aliases for ', ' (which handles both cases
in OrderedSet).', 'OrderedSet was implemented by Elia Robyn Lake (maiden name: Robyn Speer).
Jon Crall contributed changes and tests to make it fit the Python set API.
Roman Inflianskas added the original type annotations.', 'The original implementation of OrderedSet was a ', ' by Raymond Hettiger, released under the MIT license.', "Hettiger's implementation kept its content in a doubly-linked list referenced by a
dict. As a result, looking up an item by its index was an O(N) operation, while
deletion was O(1).", 'This version makes different trade-offs for the sake of efficient lookups. Its
content is a standard Python list instead of a doubly-linked list. This
provides O(1) lookups by index at the expense of O(N) deletion, as well as
slightly faster iteration.', 'In Python 3.6 and later, the built-in ', ' type is inherently ordered. If you
ignore the dictionary values, that also gives you a simple ordered set, with
fast O(1) insertion, deletion, iteration and membership testing. However, ', '
does not provide the list-like random access features of OrderedSet. You
would have to convert it to a list in O(N) to look up the index of an entry or
look up an entry by its index.', "
      A mutable set that remembers the order of its entries. One of Python's missing data types.
